WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.179 --> 00:00:03.214
So I talked a lot about the motivations,
the different paths.

2
00:00:03.214 --> 00:00:06.618
But let's get a little more
tactical on what does it

3
00:00:06.618 --> 00:00:10.666
look like to move into management,
the actual transition.

4
00:00:10.666 --> 00:00:13.914
So we had an interview earlier
with Ryan Burgess, and

5
00:00:13.914 --> 00:00:18.185
he talked about his path to management,
and his was more accidental.

6
00:00:18.185 --> 00:00:21.507
And really,
there's two ways to do things in life.

7
00:00:21.507 --> 00:00:25.829
There's accidentally doing something and
deliberately doing something.

8
00:00:25.829 --> 00:00:29.320
Maybe one's easier than the other,
but they are both valid.

9
00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:34.268
I'd say a lot of cases in people
I talk to, the accidental case,

10
00:00:34.268 --> 00:00:37.853
the accidental manager
is more likely story.

11
00:00:37.853 --> 00:00:41.147
A lot of people don't set out to
become managers, I certainly didn't.

12
00:00:41.147 --> 00:00:43.707
In my software engineering career,
I got my CS degree,

13
00:00:43.707 --> 00:00:45.346
ready to go into the world and code.

14
00:00:45.346 --> 00:00:50.660
I was not like,
I'm gonna be a great manager someday,

15
00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:53.011
far back as you can think.

16
00:00:53.011 --> 00:00:55.881
So a lot of people's paths are accidental.

17
00:00:55.881 --> 00:00:58.696
Mine was a little bit more planned,
more deliberate, but

18
00:00:58.696 --> 00:01:01.234
it was never my long-term
goal to become a manager.

19
00:01:01.234 --> 00:01:07.003
The accidental case happens all the time,
a rapidly growing company, which is great.

20
00:01:07.003 --> 00:01:10.350
You're at a startup,
it's growing, it's growing,

21
00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:12.927
it's growing, you're a manager, why?

22
00:01:12.927 --> 00:01:14.608
Cuz you've been at the company for
six months and

23
00:01:14.608 --> 00:01:16.667
that's six months longer than
everybody else on the team.

24
00:01:16.667 --> 00:01:20.445
You're now a manager,
that happens all the time.

25
00:01:20.445 --> 00:01:24.606
Or you're the best software
engineer on the team,

26
00:01:24.606 --> 00:01:28.876
the team needs a manager,
you're now the manager.

27
00:01:28.876 --> 00:01:29.956
Let me stress this again,

28
00:01:29.956 --> 00:01:33.157
being a good software engineer does not
translate into being a good manager.

29
00:01:33.157 --> 00:01:37.165
In fact, consider it the opposite,
if you're a really good software engineer,

30
00:01:37.165 --> 00:01:41.369
that means you're good at shipping and
specing things, delivering things on time.

31
00:01:41.369 --> 00:01:44.111
And you're gonna pull something
of your core competency and

32
00:01:44.111 --> 00:01:46.110
move them into an entirely different role.

33
00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:49.672
That doesn't make any sense,
but that's usually the case.

34
00:01:49.672 --> 00:01:54.171
Sometimes the manager is just the best
software engineer on the team,

35
00:01:54.171 --> 00:01:57.382
which is kind of weird to me,
but it happens a lot.

36
00:01:57.382 --> 00:02:02.705
In other cases the engineering
management team leaves and

37
00:02:02.705 --> 00:02:08.253
they're like, eeny meeny miny you,
you're now manager.

38
00:02:08.253 --> 00:02:12.776
We chuckled, but it happens, this is
how a lot of people become managers.

39
00:02:12.776 --> 00:02:14.963
And you're like, crap,
and you sink or swim.

40
00:02:14.963 --> 00:02:19.498
And the problem is if you sink,
you pull everybody down with you.

41
00:02:19.498 --> 00:02:23.054
If you swim, it's gonna be a hard swim,
the boat's really far away,

42
00:02:23.054 --> 00:02:23.972
land is far away.

43
00:02:26.668 --> 00:02:30.804
Another accidental path is the team
lead to engineering manager.

44
00:02:30.804 --> 00:02:34.083
So a team lead, this varies from
company-to-company, but generally,

45
00:02:34.083 --> 00:02:37.008
you're a technical person,
you're still doing day-to-day.

46
00:02:37.008 --> 00:02:40.523
But you're also responsible for
project management,

47
00:02:40.523 --> 00:02:43.672
the OKRs, the roadmap planning,
the strategy.

48
00:02:43.672 --> 00:02:47.368
A lot of times that's the team lead,
and they kind of accidentally

49
00:02:47.368 --> 00:02:51.137
become the manager, even though
that was not really their intent.

50
00:02:51.137 --> 00:02:54.125
In my mind, team lead does
something a little bit different,

51
00:02:54.125 --> 00:02:55.971
they're more the technical leader.

52
00:02:55.971 --> 00:02:59.288
I have team leads, they're not officially
that but I do lean on them for

53
00:02:59.288 --> 00:03:00.742
technical side and planning.

54
00:03:00.742 --> 00:03:04.466
But I still do all the overall
strategy and things like that.

55
00:03:04.466 --> 00:03:06.902
But oftentimes the team lead
becomes the engineering manager and

56
00:03:06.902 --> 00:03:07.837
you don't even know it.

57
00:03:07.837 --> 00:03:10.827
A lot of times you're a manager and
you don't even know it, just people start

58
00:03:10.827 --> 00:03:13.827
thinking of you that way, cuz you're
the person who's the face of the team.

59
00:03:13.827 --> 00:03:18.299
You're the one sending out emails,
you're the one running slack,

60
00:03:18.299 --> 00:03:19.929
that's pretty common.

61
00:03:19.929 --> 00:03:24.891
And then there's the deliberate path,
that's where you actively apply for roles.

62
00:03:24.891 --> 00:03:30.196
I'm a software engineer, I wanna
become a manager, this is what I did.

63
00:03:30.196 --> 00:03:33.564
And we'll talk about the challenges there.

64
00:03:33.564 --> 00:03:36.251
And sometimes it's deliberate,
if your company is well-structured,

65
00:03:36.251 --> 00:03:37.604
